Photos match Yellow-legged gull (L. michahellis) -or- European herring gull (L argantatus).  Head shape, bill shape, and mantle color seem better for L. michahellis, but that is subtle.  In some photos, the legs seem to appear yellow.  [Note:  As pointed out by eBird reviewer, RN, Herring gulls do not occur in this area during the summer.] All others in Herring gull complex eliminated by either mantle color, iris color, wing tip pattern, or bill shape.  Of the ones on this eBird list, the other candidates are eliminated as follows: -- Common gull (Larus canus):  bill tiny and without red spot. -- Caspian gull (Larus cachinnans):  dark iris, bill usually more slender, (mantle a bit darker??) -- Lesser black-backed gull (Larus fuscus):  mantle much too dark Other gulls in the complex not on the list: -- Glaucous gull (Larus hyperboreus):  lacks dark wingtips -- Heuglin's gull (Larus heuglini):  mantle too dark, wing tip windows don't match -- Armenian gull (Larus armenicus):  mantle too dark, wing tip wrong, iris dark

Observation Details: I originally id'd this bird as a Greater Scaup.  My thanks to Raphaël Nussbaumer and his Swiss colleagues who questioned the identification based on several characteristics and because the GRSC is fairly rare in Switzerland and is apparently often confused with the female TUDU.  Their records show the GRSC can occur as early as October, but average numbers of sightings are very low, averaging only 10 birds for the entire country in the first third of the month.  The bird in my photo is apparently preening, showing its white breast and gray flanks which I mistook for side and back of the GRSC.  However, a small portion of the black back of the TUDU is visible, and I missed this.  Also, it was pointed out that the nail or black tip of the bill is larger than seen in the GRSC and the fairly discernible white band behind it is characteristic for the TUDU but is not  seen in the GRSC.  I did not see the tuft while observing the bird and this is the only photo I took.  Hindsight is wonderful!  I will take more photos next time.  Again my thanks to Raphaël and colleagues for their very courteous help in clarifying this mistake on my part.
